# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: johnson-all-pairs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] The **Bellman–Ford algorithm** is an algorithm that computes shortest paths from a single source vertex to all of the other vertices in a weighted digraph.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] It is slower than Dijkstra's algorithm for the same problem, but more versatile, as it is capable of handling graphs in which some of the edge weights are negative numbers.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] The algorithm was first proposed by Alfonso Shimbel (1955), but is instead named after Richard Bellman and Lester Ford Jr., who published it in 1958 and 1956, respectively.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Moore also published a variation of the algorithm in 1959, and for this reason it is also sometimes called the **Bellman–Ford–Moore algorithm**.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Negative edge weights are found in various applications of graphs.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] If a graph contains a "negative cycle" (i.e. a cycle whose edges sum to a negative value) that is reachable from the source, then there is no *cheapest* path: any path that has a point on the negative cycle can be made cheaper by one more walk around the negative cycle.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] In such a case, the Bellman–Ford algorithm can detect and report the negative cycle.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Like Dijkstra's algorithm, Bellman–Ford proceeds by relaxation, in which approximations to the correct distance are replaced by better ones until they eventually reach the solution.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] In both algorithms, the approximate distance to each vertex is always an overestimate of the true distance, and is replaced by the minimum of its old value and the length of a newly found path.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] In each of these repetitions, the number of vertices with correctly calculated distances grows, from which it follows that eventually all vertices will have their correct distances.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] This method allows the Bellman–Ford algorithm to be applied to a wider class of inputs than Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] The intermediate answers and the choices among equally short paths depend on the order of edges relaxed, but the final distances remain the same.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Bellman–Ford runs in $O(|V|\cdot |E|)$ time, where $|V|$ and $|E|$ are the number of vertices and edges respectively.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Simply put, the algorithm initializes the distance to the source to 0 and all other nodes to infinity.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Then for all edges, if the distance to the destination can be shortened by taking the edge, the distance is updated to the new lower value.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] The core of the algorithm is a loop that scans across all edges at every loop.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Since the longest possible path without a cycle can be $|V|-1$ edges, the edges must be scanned $|V|-1$ times to ensure the shortest path has been found for all nodes.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] A final scan of all the edges is performed and if any distance is updated, then a path of length $|V|$ edges has been found which can only occur if at least one negative cycle exists in the graph.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] The edge (u, v) that is found in step 3 must be reachable from a negative cycle, but it isn't necessarily part of the cycle itself, which is why it's necessary to follow the path of predecessors backwards until a cycle is detected.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] The above pseudo-code uses a Boolean array (`visited`) to find a vertex on the cycle, but any cycle finding algorithm can be used to find a vertex on the cycle.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] A common improvement when implementing the algorithm is to return early when an iteration of step 2 fails to relax any edges, which implies all shortest paths have been found, and therefore there are no negative cycles.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] In that case, the complexity of the algorithm is reduced from $O(|V|\cdot |E|)$ to $O(l\cdot |E|)$ where l is the maximum length of a shortest path in the graph.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] For the inductive case, we first prove the first part.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Consider a moment when a vertex's distance is updated by `v.distance := u.distance + uv.weight`.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] By inductive assumption, `u.distance` is the length of some path from *source* to *u*.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Then `u.distance + uv.weight` is the length of the path from *source* to *v* that follows the path from *source* to *u* and then goes to *v*.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] For the second part, consider a shortest path *P* (there may be more than one) from *source* to *v* with at most *i* edges.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Let *u* be the last vertex before *v* on this path.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] By inductive assumption, `u.distance` after *i*−1 iterations is at most the length of this path from *source* to *u*.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Therefore, `uv.weight + u.distance` is at most the length of *P*.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] In the *ith* iteration, `v.distance` gets compared with `uv.weight + u.distance`, and is set equal to it if `uv.weight + u.distance` is smaller.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Therefore, after *i* iterations, `v.distance` is at most the length of *P*, i.e., the length of the shortest path from *source* to *v* that uses at most *i* edges.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] If there are no negative-weight cycles, then every shortest path visits each vertex at most once, so at step 3 no further improvements can be made.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Conversely, suppose no improvement can be made.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] I.e., every cycle has nonnegative weight.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] When the algorithm is used to find shortest paths, the existence of negative cycles is a problem, preventing the algorithm from finding a correct answer.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] However, since it terminates upon finding a negative cycle, the Bellman–Ford algorithm can be used for applications in which this is the target to be sought – for example in cycle-cancelling techniques in network flow analysis.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] A distributed variant of the Bellman–Ford algorithm is used in distance-vector routing protocols, for example the Routing Information Protocol (RIP).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] The algorithm is distributed because it involves a number of nodes (routers) within an Autonomous system (AS), a collection of IP networks typically owned by an ISP.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Each node sends its table to all neighboring nodes.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] When a node receives distance tables from its neighbors, it calculates the shortest routes to all other nodes and updates its own table to reflect any changes.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] With this early termination condition, the main loop may in some cases use many fewer than |*V*| − 1 iterations, even though the worst case of the algorithm remains unchanged.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] The following improvements all maintain the $O(|V|\cdot |E|)$ worst-case time complexity.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] A variation of the Bellman–Ford algorithm described by Moore (1959), reduces the number of relaxation steps that need to be performed within each iteration of the algorithm.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] If a vertex *v* has a distance value that has not changed since the last time the edges out of *v* were relaxed, then there is no need to relax the edges out of *v* a second time.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] In this way, as the number of vertices with correct distance values grows, the number whose outgoing edges that need to be relaxed in each iteration shrinks, leading to a constant-factor savings in time for dense graphs.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] This variation can be implemented by keeping a collection of vertices whose outgoing edges need to be relaxed, removing a vertex from this collection when its edges are relaxed, and adding to the collection any vertex whose distance value is changed by a relaxation step.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] In China, this algorithm was popularized by Fanding Duan, who rediscovered it in 1994, as the "shortest path faster algorithm".
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Yen (1970) described another improvement to the Bellman–Ford algorithm.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] His improvement first assigns some arbitrary linear order on all vertices and then partitions the set of all edges into two subsets.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] The first subset, *Ef*, contains all edges (*vi*, *vj*) such that *i* < *j*; the second, *Eb*, contains edges (*vi*, *vj*) such that *i* > *j*.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Each vertex is visited in the order *v1*, *v2*, ..., *v*|*V*|, relaxing each outgoing edge from that vertex in *Ef*.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Each vertex is then visited in the order *v*|*V*|, *v*|*V*|−1, ..., *v*1, relaxing each outgoing edge from that vertex in *Eb*.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Each iteration of the main loop of the algorithm, after the first one, adds at least two edges to the set of edges whose relaxed distances match the correct shortest path distances: one from *Ef* and one from *Eb*.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] This modification reduces the worst-case number of iterations of the main loop of the algorithm from |*V*| − 1 to $|V|/2$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Another improvement, by Bannister & Eppstein (2012), replaces the arbitrary linear order of the vertices used in Yen's second improvement by a random permutation.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] This change makes the worst case for Yen's improvement (in which the edges of a shortest path strictly alternate between the two subsets *Ef* and *Eb*) very unlikely to happen.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] With a randomly permuted vertex ordering, the expected number of iterations needed in the main loop is at most $|V|/3$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Fineman (2024), at Georgetown University, created an improved algorithm that with high probability runs in ${\tilde {O}}(|V|^{8/9}\cdot |E|)$ time.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/bellman-ford-algorithm] Here, the ${\tilde {O}}$ is a variant of big O notation that hides logarithmic factors.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm finds the shortest path from a given source node to every other node.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It can be used to find the shortest path to a specific destination node, by terminating the algorithm after determining the shortest path to that node.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if the nodes of the graph represent cities, and the costs of edges represent the distances between pairs of cities connected by a direct road, then Dijkstra's algorithm can be used to find the shortest route between one city and all other cities.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A common application of shortest path algorithms is network routing protocols, most notably IS-IS (Intermediate System to Intermediate System) and OSPF (Open Shortest Path First).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It is also employed as a subroutine in algorithms such as Johnson's algorithm.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The algorithm uses a min-priority queue data structure for selecting the shortest paths known so far.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Before more advanced priority queue structures were discovered, Dijkstra's original algorithm ran in $\Theta (|V|^{2})$ time, where $|V|$ is the number of nodes.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Fredman & Tarjan 1984 proposed a Fibonacci heap priority queue to optimize the running time complexity to $\Theta (|E|+|V|\log |V|)$ , where $|E|$ is the number of edges.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This is asymptotically the fastest known single-source shortest-path algorithm for arbitrary directed graphs with unbounded non-negative weights.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] However, specialized cases (such as bounded/integer weights, directed acyclic graphs etc.) can be improved further.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If preprocessing is allowed, algorithms such as contraction hierarchies can be up to seven orders of magnitude faster.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm is commonly used on graphs where the edge weights are positive integers or real numbers.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It can be generalized to any graph where the edge weights are partially ordered, provided the subsequent labels (a subsequent label is produced when traversing an edge) are monotonically non-decreasing.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In many fields, particularly artificial intelligence, Dijkstra's algorithm or a variant offers a uniform cost search and is formulated as an instance of the more general idea of best-first search.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] — Edsger Dijkstra, in an interview with Philip L.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra thought about the shortest path problem while working as a programmer at the Mathematical Center in Amsterdam in 1956.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] He wanted to demonstrate the capabilities of the new ARMAC computer.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] His objective was to choose a problem and a computer solution that non-computing people could understand.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] He designed the shortest path algorithm and later implemented it for ARMAC for a slightly simplified transportation map of 64 cities in the Netherlands (he limited it to 64, so that 6 bits would be sufficient to encode the city number).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A year later, he came across another problem advanced by hardware engineers working on the institute's next computer: minimize the amount of wire needed to connect the pins on the machine's back panel.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] As a solution, he re-discovered Prim's minimal spanning tree algorithm (known earlier to Jarník, and also rediscovered by Prim).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra published the algorithm in 1959, two years after Prim and 29 years after Jarník.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The algorithm requires a starting node, and computes the shortest distance from that starting node to each other node.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Assign to every node a distance from start value: for the starting node, it is zero, and for all other nodes, it is infinity, since initially no path is known to these nodes.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] During execution, the distance of a node *N* is the length of the shortest path discovered so far between the starting node and *N*.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] From the unvisited set, select the current node to be the one with the smallest (finite) distance; initially, this is the starting node (distance zero).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the unvisited set is empty, or contains only nodes with infinite distance (which are unreachable), then the algorithm terminates by skipping to step 6.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the only concern is the path to a target node, the algorithm terminates once the current node is the target node.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For the current node, consider all of its unvisited neighbors and update their distances through the current node; compare the newly calculated distance to the one currently assigned to the neighbor and assign the smaller one to it.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if the current node *A* is marked with a distance of 6, and the edge connecting it with its neighbor *B* has length 2, then the distance to *B* through *A* is 6 + 2 = 8.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If B was previously marked with a distance greater than 8, then update it to 8 (the path to B through A is shorter).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Otherwise, keep its current distance (the path to B through A is not the shortest).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After considering all of the current node's unvisited neighbors, the current node is removed from the unvisited set.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Thus a visited node is never rechecked, which is correct because the distance recorded on the current node is minimal (as ensured in step 3), and thus final.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Once the loop exits (steps 3–5), every visited node contains its shortest distance from the starting node.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The shortest path between two intersections on a city map can be found by this algorithm using pencil and paper.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Every intersection is listed on a separate line: one is the starting point and is labeled (given a distance of) 0.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Every other intersection is initially labeled with a distance of infinity.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This is done to note that no path to these intersections has yet been established.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] At each iteration one intersection becomes the current intersection.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For the first iteration, this is the starting point.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] From the current intersection, the distance to every neighbor (directly-connected) intersection is assessed by summing the label (value) of the current intersection and the distance to the neighbor and then relabeling the neighbor with the lesser of that sum and the neighbor's existing label.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] I.e., the neighbor is relabeled if the path to it through the current intersection is shorter than previously assessed paths.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If so, mark the road to the neighbor with an arrow pointing to it, and erase any other arrow that points to it.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After the distances to each of the current intersection's neighbors have been assessed, the current intersection is marked as visited.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The unvisited intersection with the smallest label becomes the current intersection and the process repeats until all nodes with labels less than the destination's label have been visited.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Once no unvisited nodes remain with a label smaller than the destination's label, the remaining arrows show the shortest path.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In the following pseudocode, dist is an array that contains the current distances from the *source* to other vertices, i.e. dist[*u*] is the current distance from the source to the vertex *u*.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The prev array contains pointers to previous-hop nodes on the shortest path from source to the given vertex (equivalently, it is the *next-hop* on the path *from* the given vertex *to* the source).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The code u ← vertex in *Q* with min dist[u], searches for the vertex *u* in the vertex set *Q* that has the least dist[*u*] value.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Graph.Distance(*u*,*v*) returns the length of the edge joining (i.e. the distance between) the two neighbor-nodes *u* and *v*.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The variable *alt* on line 14 is the length of the path from the *source* node to the neighbor node *v* if it were to go through *u*.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If this path is shorter than the current shortest path recorded for *v*, then the distance of *v* is updated to *alt*.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To find the shortest path between vertices *source* and *target*, the search terminates after line 10 if *u* = *target*.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Now sequence *S* is the list of vertices constituting one of the shortest paths from *source* to *target*, or the empty sequence if no path exists.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A more general problem is to find all the shortest paths between *source* and *target* (there might be several of the same length).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Then instead of storing only a single node in each entry of prev[] all nodes satisfying the relaxation condition can be stored.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if both *r* and *source* connect to *target* and they lie on different shortest paths through *target* (because the edge cost is the same in both cases), then both *r* and *source* are added to prev[*target*].
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] When the algorithm completes, prev[] data structure describes a graph that is a subset of the original graph with some edges removed.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Its key property is that if the algorithm was run with some starting node, then every path from that node to any other node in the new graph is the shortest path between those nodes graph, and all paths of that length from the original graph are present in the new graph.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Then to actually find all these shortest paths between two given nodes, a path finding algorithm on the new graph, such as depth-first search would work.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A min-priority queue is an abstract data type that provides 3 basic operations: add_with_priority(), decrease_priority() and extract_min().
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] As mentioned earlier, using such a data structure can lead to faster computing times than using a basic queue.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Notably, Fibonacci heap or Brodal queue offer optimal implementations for those 3 operations.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Instead of filling the priority queue with all nodes in the initialization phase, it is possible to initialize it to contain only *source*; then, inside the `**if** *alt* < dist[*v*]` block, the decrease_priority() becomes an add_with_priority() operation.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Yet another alternative is to add nodes unconditionally to the priority queue and to instead check after extraction (`*u* ← *Q*.extract_min()`) that it isn't revisiting, or that no shorter connection was found yet in the `if alt < dist[v]` block.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This can be done by additionally extracting the associated priority `*p*` from the queue and only processing further `**if** *p* == dist[*u*]` inside the `**while** *Q* is not empty` loop.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] These alternatives can use entirely array-based priority queues without decrease-key functionality, which have been found to achieve even faster computing times in practice.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] However, the difference in performance was found to be narrower for denser graphs.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To prove the correctness of Dijkstra's algorithm, mathematical induction can be used on the number of visited nodes.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The base case is when there is just one visited node, source.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Its distance is defined to be zero, which is the shortest distance, since negative weights are not allowed.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Assuming that the hypothesis holds for k visited nodes, to show it holds for $k+1$ nodes, let u be the next visited node, i.e. the node with minimum `dist[u]`.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The claim is that `dist[u]` is the shortest distance from source to u.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If a shorter path were available, then this shorter path either contains another unvisited node or not.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For all other visited nodes v, the `dist[v]` is already known to be the shortest distance from source, because of the inductive hypothesis, and these values are unchanged.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After processing u, it is still true that for each unvisited node w, `dist[w]` is the shortest distance from source to w using visited nodes only.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Any shorter path that did not use u, would already have been found, and if a shorter path used u it would have been updated when processing u.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After all nodes are visited, the shortest path from source to any node v consists only of visited nodes.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Therefore, `dist[v]` is the shortest distance.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Bounds of the running time of Dijkstra's algorithm on a graph with edges E and vertices V can be expressed as a function of the number of edges, denoted $|E|$ , and the number of vertices, denoted $|V|$ , using big-O notation.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The complexity bound depends mainly on the data structure used to represent the set Q.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In the following, upper bounds can be simplified because $|E|$ is $O(|V|^{2})$ for any simple graph, but that simplification disregards the fact that in some problems, other upper bounds on $|E|$ may hold.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] where $T_{\mathrm {dk} }$ and $T_{\mathrm {em} }$ are the complexities of the *decrease-key* and *extract-minimum* operations in Q, respectively.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The simplest version of Dijkstra's algorithm stores the vertex set Q as a linked list or array, and edges as an adjacency list or matrix.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In this case, extract-minimum is simply a linear search through all vertices in Q, so the running time is ${\textstyle \Theta (|E|+|V|^{2})=\Theta (|V|^{2})}$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To perform decrease-key steps in a binary heap efficiently, it is necessary to use an auxiliary data structure that maps each vertex to its position in the heap, and to update this structure as the priority queue Q changes.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] With a self-balancing binary search tree or binary heap, the algorithm requires ${\textstyle \Theta ((|E|+|V|)\log |V|)}$ time in the worst case; for connected graphs this time bound can be simplified to ${\textstyle \Theta (|E|\log |V|)}$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The Fibonacci heap improves this to ${\textstyle \Theta (|E|+|V|\log |V|)}$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In common presentations of Dijkstra's algorithm, initially all nodes are entered into the priority queue.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This is, however, not necessary: the algorithm can start with a priority queue that contains only one item, and insert new items as they are discovered (instead of doing a decrease-key, check whether the key is in the queue; if it is, decrease its key, otherwise insert it).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This variant has the same worst-case bounds as the common variant, but maintains a smaller priority queue in practice, speeding up queue operations.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Moreover, not inserting all nodes in a graph makes it possible to extend the algorithm to find the shortest path from a single source to the closest of a set of target nodes on infinite graphs or those too large to represent in memory.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Combinations of such techniques may be needed for optimal practical performance on specific problems.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Two distance arrays are maintained: *df*[*v*] (distance from s to v) and *db*[*v*] (distance from v to t), initialized to ∞ except *df*[*s*] = 0 and *db*[*t*] = 0.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Two priority queues *Qf* and *Qb* hold vertices not yet fully processed, and two sets *Sf* and *Sb* store vertices whose shortest-path distance is finalized in each direction.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A variable μ stores the length of the best full s–t path found so far, initially ∞.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] and symmetrically for the backward search.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A key feature is the stopping condition: once the sum of the current minimum priorities in both queues is at least μ, no yet-unsettled path can improve upon μ.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] At this point μ equals the true shortest-path distance δ(*s*,*t*), and the search terminates.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This criterion avoids a common mistake of halting as soon as the two frontiers touch, which may overlook a shorter alternative crossing elsewhere.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Because each search only needs to explore roughly half of the search space in typical graphs, the bidirectional method often visits far fewer vertices and relaxes far fewer edges than one-directional Dijkstra on single-pair queries.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In road-network–like graphs the savings can be dramatic, sometimes reducing the explored region from an exponential-size ball to two smaller half-balls.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The method is widely used in point-to-point routing for maps and navigation software and serves as a base for many speed-up techniques such as the ALT, contraction hierarchies, and reach-based routing.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the actual shortest path (not just its distance) is desired, predecessor pointers can be stored in both searches.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] When μ is updated through some crossing vertex x, the algorithm records this meeting point and reconstructs the final route as the forward path from s to x concatenated with the backward path from x to t.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Theoretical research shows that an optimized bidirectional approach can be instance-optimal, meaning no correct algorithm can asymptotically relax fewer edges on the same graph instance.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Although Dijkstra's algorithm is optimal for graphs with non-negative edge weights, its practical runtime depends on both data structures and graph properties.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Using a binary heap results in a running time of O((V+E)logV).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Alternatives such as Fibonacci heaps provide better theoretical bounds but often perform worse in real applications because of large constant factors.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Graph structure also plays a major role.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Sparse networks, such as road maps, allow Dijkstra's algorithm to operate efficiently since most vertices have low degree.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dense graphs increase relaxations and slow down the process.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Because of this, modern routing systems often use Dijkstra's algorithm together with preprocessing methods such as A* search, landmark heuristics, or contraction hierarchies, which significantly reduce the search space.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Memory locality is another important factor.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Cache-optimized priority queues and adjacency layouts can reduce latency for large graphs that exceed CPU cache limitations.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Because of these considerations, most real-world systems use specialized Dijkstra variants tuned for specific graph families and hardware constraints.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] As well as simply computing distances and paths, Dijkstra's algorithm can be used to sort vertices by their distances from a given starting vertex.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To achieve this, they use a comparison-based heap whose cost of returning/removing the minimum element from the heap is logarithmic in the number of elements inserted after it rather than in the number of elements in the heap.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] When arc weights are small integers (bounded by a parameter C ), specialized queues can be used for increased speed.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The first algorithm of this type was Dial's algorithm for graphs with positive integer edge weights, which uses a bucket queue to obtain a running time $O(|E|+|V|C)$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The use of a Van Emde Boas tree as the priority queue brings the complexity to $O(|E|+|V|\log C/\log \log |V|C)$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Another interesting variant based on a combination of a new radix heap and the well-known Fibonacci heap runs in time $O(|E|+|V|{\sqrt {\log C}})$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's original algorithm can be extended with modifications.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, sometimes it is desirable to present solutions which are less than mathematically optimal.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To obtain a ranked list of less-than-optimal solutions, the optimal solution is first calculated.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A single edge appearing in the optimal solution is removed from the graph, and the optimum solution to this new graph is calculated.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Each edge of the original solution is suppressed in turn and a new shortest-path calculated.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The secondary solutions are then ranked and presented after the first optimal solution.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm is usually the working principle behind link-state routing protocols.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Unlike Dijkstra's algorithm, the Bellman–Ford algorithm can be used on graphs with negative edge weights, as long as the graph contains no negative cycle reachable from the source vertex *s*.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The presence of such cycles means that no shortest path can be found, since the label becomes lower each time the cycle is traversed.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] (This statement assumes that a "path" is allowed to repeat vertices.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In graph theory that is normally not allowed.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In theoretical computer science it often is allowed.) It is possible to adapt Dijkstra's algorithm to handle negative weights by combining it with the Bellman-Ford algorithm (to remove negative edges and detect negative cycles): Johnson's algorithm.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The A* algorithm is a generalization of Dijkstra's algorithm that reduces the size of the subgraph that must be explored, if additional information is available that provides a lower bound on the distance to the target.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The process that underlies Dijkstra's algorithm is similar to the greedy process used in Prim's algorithm.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Prim's purpose is to find a minimum spanning tree that connects all nodes in the graph; Dijkstra is concerned with only two nodes.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Prim's does not evaluate the total weight of the path from the starting node, only the individual edges.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Breadth-first search can be viewed as a special-case of Dijkstra's algorithm on unweighted graphs, where the priority queue degenerates into a FIFO queue.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The fast marching method can be viewed as a continuous version of Dijkstra's algorithm which computes the geodesic distance on a triangle mesh.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] From a dynamic programming point of view, Dijkstra's algorithm is a successive approximation scheme that solves the dynamic programming functional equation for the shortest path problem by the **Reaching** method.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/dijkstra-s-algorithm] is a paraphrasing of Bellman's principle of optimality in the context of the shortest path problem.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] Second, the Bellman–Ford algorithm is used, starting from the new vertex q, to find for each vertex v the minimum weight *h*(*v*) of a path from q to v.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] If this step detects a negative cycle, the algorithm is terminated.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] Next the edges of the original graph are reweighted using the values computed by the Bellman–Ford algorithm: an edge from u to v, having length ⁠ $w(u,v)$ ⁠, is given the new length *w*(*u*,*v*) + *h*(*u*) − *h*(*v*).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] Finally, q is removed, and Dijkstra's algorithm is used to find the shortest paths from each node s to every other vertex in the reweighted graph.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] The distance in the original graph is then computed for each distance D(u, v), by adding *h*(*v*) − *h*(*u*) to the distance returned by Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] The first three stages of Johnson's algorithm are depicted in the illustration below.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] The graph on the left of the illustration has two negative edges, but no negative cycles.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] The center graph shows the new vertex q, a shortest path tree as computed by the Bellman–Ford algorithm with q as starting vertex, and the values *h*(*v*) computed at each other node as the length of the shortest path from q to that node.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] Note that these values are all non-positive, because q has a length-zero edge to each vertex and the shortest path can be no longer than that edge.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] On the right is shown the reweighted graph, formed by replacing each edge weight ⁠ $w(u,v)$ ⁠ by *w*(*u*,*v*) + *h*(*u*) − *h*(*v*).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] In this reweighted graph, all edge weights are non-negative, but the shortest path between any two nodes uses the same sequence of edges as the shortest path between the same two nodes in the original graph.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] The algorithm concludes by applying Dijkstra's algorithm to each of the four starting nodes in the reweighted graph.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] In the reweighted graph, all paths between a pair s and t of nodes have the same quantity *h*(*s*) − *h*(*t*) added to them.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] The previous statement can be proven as follows: Let p be an ⁠ $s-t$ ⁠ path.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] The bracketed expression is the weight of *p* in the original weighting.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] Since the reweighting adds the same amount to the weight of every ⁠ $s-t$ ⁠ path, a path is a shortest path in the original weighting if and only if it is a shortest path after reweighting.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] The weight of edges that belong to a shortest path from *q* to any node is zero, and therefore the lengths of the shortest paths from *q* to every node become zero in the reweighted graph; however, they still remain shortest paths.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] Therefore, there can be no negative edges: if edge *uv* had a negative weight after the reweighting, then the zero-length path from *q* to *u* together with this edge would form a negative-length path from *q* to *v*, contradicting the fact that all vertices have zero distance from *q*.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] The non-existence of negative edges ensures the optimality of the paths found by Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] The distances in the original graph may be calculated from the distances calculated by Dijkstra's algorithm in the reweighted graph by reversing the reweighting transformation.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/johnson-s-algorithm] Thus, when the graph is sparse, the total time can be faster than the Floyd–Warshall algorithm, which solves the same problem in time $O(|V|^{3})$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] In graph theory, **reachability** refers to the ability to get from one vertex to another within a graph.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] A vertex s can reach a vertex t (and t is reachable from s ) if there exists a sequence of adjacent vertices (i.e. a walk) which starts with s and ends with t .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] In an undirected graph, reachability between all pairs of vertices can be determined by identifying the connected components of the graph.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] Any pair of vertices in such a graph can reach each other if and only if they belong to the same connected component; therefore, in such a graph, reachability is symmetric ( s reaches t iff t reaches s ).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] The connected components of an undirected graph can be identified in linear time.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] The remainder of this article focuses on the more difficult problem of determining pairwise reachability in a directed graph (which, incidentally, need not be symmetric).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] If G is acyclic, then its reachability relation is a partial order; any partial order may be defined in this way, for instance as the reachability relation of its transitive reduction.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] A noteworthy consequence of this is that since partial orders are anti-symmetric, if s can reach t , then we know that t *cannot* reach s .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] Intuitively, if we could travel from s to t and back to s , then G would contain a cycle, contradicting that it is acyclic.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] If G is directed but *not* acyclic (i.e. it contains at least one cycle), then its reachability relation will correspond to a preorder instead of a partial order.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] Algorithms for determining reachability fall into two classes: those that require preprocessing and those that do not.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] If you have only one (or a few) queries to make, it may be more efficient to forgo the use of more complex data structures and compute the reachability of the desired pair directly.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] This can be accomplished in linear time using algorithms such as breadth first search or iterative deepening depth-first search.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] If you will be making many queries, then a more sophisticated method may be used; the exact choice of method depends on the nature of the graph being analysed.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] In exchange for preprocessing time and some extra storage space, we can create a data structure which can then answer reachability queries on any pair of vertices in as low as $O(1)$ time.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] Three different algorithms and data structures for three different, increasingly specialized situations are outlined below.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] The Floyd–Warshall algorithm can be used to compute the transitive closure of any directed graph, which gives rise to the reachability relation as in the definition, above.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] The algorithm requires $O(|V|^{3})$ time and $O(|V|^{2})$ space in the worst case.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] This algorithm is not solely interested in reachability as it also computes the shortest path distance between all pairs of vertices.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] For graphs containing negative cycles, shortest paths may be undefined, but reachability between pairs can still be noted.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] For planar digraphs, a much faster method is available, as described by Mikkel Thorup in 2004.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] This method can answer reachability queries on a planar graph in $O(1)$ time after spending $O(n\log {n})$ preprocessing time to create a data structure of $O(n\log {n})$ size.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] This algorithm can also supply approximate shortest path distances, as well as route information.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] The overall approach is to associate with each vertex a relatively small set of so-called separator paths such that any path from a vertex v to any other vertex w must go through at least one of the separators associated with v or w .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] An outline of the reachability related sections follows.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] Given a graph G , the algorithm begins by organizing the vertices into layers starting from an arbitrary vertex $v_{0}$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] The layers are built in alternating steps by first considering all vertices reachable *from* the previous step (starting with just $v_{0}$ ) and then all vertices which reach *to* the previous step until all vertices have been assigned to a layer.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] By construction of the layers, every vertex appears at most two layers, and every directed path, or dipath, in G is contained within two adjacent layers $L_{i}$ and $L_{i+1}$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] Let k be the last layer created, that is, the lowest value for k such that $\bigcup _{i=0}^{k}L_{i}=V$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] The graph is then re-expressed as a series of digraphs $G_{0},G_{1},\ldots ,G_{k-1}$ where each $G_{i}=r_{i}\cup L_{i}\cup L_{i+1}$ and where $r_{i}$ is the contraction of all previous levels $L_{0}\ldots L_{i-1}$ into a single vertex.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] For each $G_{i}$ , three separators are identified which, when removed, break the graph into three components which each contain at most $1/2$ the vertices of the original.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] As $G_{i}$ is built from two layers of opposed dipaths, each separator may consist of up to 2 dipaths, for a total of up to 6 dipaths over all of the separators.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] The proof that such separators can always be found is related to the Planar Separator Theorem of Lipton and Tarjan, and these separators can be located in linear time.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] For each $Q\in S$ , the directed nature of Q provides for a natural indexing of its vertices from the start to the end of the path.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] For each vertex v in $G_{i}$ , we locate the first vertex in Q reachable by v , and the last vertex in Q that reaches to v .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] That is, we are looking at how early into Q we can get from v , and how far we can stay in Q and still get back to v .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] This information is stored with each v .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] Then for any pair of vertices u and w , u can reach w *via* Q if u connects to Q earlier than w connects from Q .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] Every vertex is labelled as above for each step of the recursion which builds $G_{0}\ldots ,G_{k}$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] As this recursion has logarithmic depth, a total of $O(\log {n})$ extra information is stored per vertex.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] From this point, a logarithmic time query for reachability is as simple as looking over each pair of labels for a common, suitable Q .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] The original paper then works to tune the query time down to $O(1)$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] In summarizing the analysis of this method, first consider that the layering approach partitions the vertices so that each vertex is considered only $O(1)$ times.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] The separator phase of the algorithm breaks the graph into components which are at most $1/2$ the size of the original graph, resulting in a logarithmic recursion depth.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] At each level of the recursion, only linear work is needed to identify the separators as well as the connections possible between vertices.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] The overall result is $O(n\log n)$ preprocessing time with only $O(\log {n})$ additional information stored for each vertex.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] An even faster method for pre-processing, due to T.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] If G exhibits these properties, then we can preprocess the graph in only $O(n)$ time, and store only $O(\log {n})$ extra bits per vertex, answering reachability queries for any pair of vertices in $O(1)$ time with a simple comparison.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] Preprocessing performs the following steps.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] We add a new vertex s which has an edge to each 0-indegree vertex, and another new vertex t with edges from each 0-outdegree vertex.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] Note that the properties of G allow us to do so while maintaining planarity, that is, there will still be no edge crossings after these additions.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] For each vertex we store the list of adjacencies (out-edges) in order of the planarity of the graph (for example, clockwise with respect to the graph's embedding).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] We then initialize a counter $i=n+1$ and begin a Depth-First Traversal from s .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] During this traversal, the adjacency list of each vertex is visited from left-to-right as needed.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] As vertices are popped from the traversal's stack, they are labelled with the value i , and i is then decremented.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] Note that t is always labelled with the value $n+1$ and s is always labelled with 0 .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] The depth-first traversal is then repeated, but this time the adjacency list of each vertex is visited from right-to-left.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] When completed, s and t , and their incident edges, are removed.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] Each remaining vertex stores a 2-dimensional label with values from 1 to n .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] The main result of this method then states that v is reachable from u if and only if $L(u)<L(v)$ , which is easily calculated in $O(1)$ time.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] A related problem is to solve reachability queries with some number k of vertex failures.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] For example: "Can vertex u still reach vertex v even though vertices $s_{1},s_{2},...,s_{k}$ have failed and can no longer be used?" A similar problem may consider edge failures rather than vertex failures, or a mix of the two.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] The breadth-first search technique works just as well on such queries, but constructing an efficient oracle is more challenging.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] Another problem related to reachability queries is in quickly recalculating changes to reachability relationships when some portion of the graph is changed.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/reachability] For example, this is a relevant concern to garbage collection which needs to balance the reclamation of memory (so that it may be reallocated) with the performance concerns of the running application.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] In graph theory, the **shortest path problem** is the problem of finding a path between two vertices (or nodes) in a graph such that the sum of the weights of its constituent edges is minimized.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The problem of finding the shortest path between two intersections on a road map may be modeled as a special case of the shortest path problem in graphs, where the vertices correspond to intersections and the edges correspond to road segments, each weighted by the length or distance of each segment.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The shortest path problem can be defined for graphs whether undirected, directed, or mixed.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The definition for undirected graphs states that every edge can be traversed in either direction.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Directed graphs require that consecutive vertices be connected by an appropriate directed edge.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Two vertices are adjacent when they are both incident to a common edge.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] A path in an undirected graph is a sequence of vertices $P=(v_{1},v_{2},\ldots ,v_{n})\in V\times V\times \cdots \times V$ such that $v_{i}$ is adjacent to $v_{i+1}$ for $1\leq i<n$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Such a path P is called a path of length $n-1$ from $v_{1}$ to $v_{n}$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] These generalizations have significantly more efficient algorithms than the simplistic approach of running a single-pair shortest path algorithm on all relevant pairs of vertices.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Several well-known algorithms exist for solving this problem and its variants.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Additional algorithms and associated evaluations may be found in Cherkassky, Goldberg & Radzik (1996).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] An algorithm using topological sorting can solve the single-source shortest path problem in time Θ(*E* + *V*) in arbitrarily-weighted directed acyclic graphs.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The following table is taken from Schrijver (2004), with some corrections and additions.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] A green background indicates an asymptotically best bound in the table; *L* is the maximum length (or weight) among all edges, assuming integer edge weights.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Finds a negative cycle or calculates distances to all vertices.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The all-pairs shortest path problem finds the shortest paths between every pair of vertices v, v' in the graph.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The all-pairs shortest paths problem for unweighted directed graphs was introduced by Shimbel (1953), who observed that it could be solved by a linear number of matrix multiplications that takes a total time of *O*(*V*4).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Shortest path algorithms are applied to automatically find directions between physical locations, such as driving directions on web mapping websites like MapQuest or Google Maps.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] For this application fast specialized algorithms are available.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] For example, if vertices represent the states of a puzzle like a Rubik's Cube and each directed edge corresponds to a single move or turn, shortest path algorithms can be used to find a solution that uses the minimum possible number of moves.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] In a networking or telecommunications mindset, this shortest path problem is sometimes called the min-delay path problem and usually tied with a widest path problem.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] For example, the algorithm may seek the shortest (min-delay) widest path, or widest shortest (min-delay) path.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] A more lighthearted application is the games of "six degrees of separation" that try to find the shortest path in graphs like movie stars appearing in the same film.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Other applications, often studied in operations research, include plant and facility layout, robotics, transportation, and VLSI design.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] A road network can be considered as a graph with positive weights.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The nodes represent road junctions and each edge of the graph is associated with a road segment between two junctions.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The weight of an edge may correspond to the length of the associated road segment, the time needed to traverse the segment, or the cost of traversing the segment.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Using directed edges it is also possible to model one-way streets.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Such graphs are special in the sense that some edges are more important than others for long-distance travel (e.g. highways).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] This property has been formalized using the notion of highway dimension.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] There are a great number of algorithms that exploit this property and are therefore able to compute the shortest path a lot quicker than would be possible on general graphs.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] All of these algorithms work in two phases.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] In the first phase, the graph is preprocessed without knowing the source or target node.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] In this phase, source and target node are known.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The idea is that the road network is static, so the preprocessing phase can be done once and used for a large number of queries on the same road network.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The algorithm with the fastest known query time is called hub labeling and is able to compute shortest path on the road networks of Europe or the US in a fraction of a microsecond.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] For shortest path problems in computational geometry, see Euclidean shortest path.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The shortest multiple disconnected path is a representation of the primitive path network within the framework of Reptation theory.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The widest path problem seeks a path so that the minimum label of any edge is as large as possible.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Other related problems may be classified into the following categories.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Unlike the shortest path problem, which can be solved in polynomial time in graphs without negative cycles, shortest path problems which include additional constraints on the desired solution path are called Constrained Shortest Path First, and are harder to solve.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] One example is the constrained shortest path problem, which attempts to minimize the total cost of the path while at the same time maintaining another metric below a given threshold.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] This makes the problem NP-complete (such problems are not believed to be efficiently solvable for large sets of data, see P = NP problem).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Another NP-complete example requires a specific set of vertices to be included in the path, which makes the problem similar to the Traveling Salesman Problem (TSP).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The TSP is the problem of finding the shortest path that goes through every vertex exactly once, and returns to the start.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The problem of finding the longest path in a graph is also NP-complete.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The Canadian traveller problem and the stochastic shortest path problem are generalizations where either the graph is not completely known to the mover, changes over time, or where actions (traversals) are probabilistic.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Sometimes, the edges in a graph have personalities: each edge has its own selfish interest.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] An example is a communication network, in which each edge is a computer that possibly belongs to a different person.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Different computers have different transmission speeds, so every edge in the network has a numeric weight equal to the number of milliseconds it takes to transmit a message.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Our goal is to send a message between two points in the network in the shortest time possible.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] If we know the transmission-time of each computer (the weight of each edge), then we can use a standard shortest-paths algorithm.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] If we do not know the transmission times, then we have to ask each computer to tell us its transmission-time.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] But, the computers may be selfish: a computer might tell us that its transmission time is very long, so that we will not bother it with our messages.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] A possible solution to this problem is to use a variant of the VCG mechanism, which gives the computers an incentive to reveal their true weights.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] In some cases, the main goal is not to find the shortest path, but only to detect if the graph contains a negative cycle.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Many problems can be framed as a form of the shortest path for some suitably substituted notions of addition along a path and taking the minimum.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The general approach to these is to consider the two operations to be those of a semiring.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Semiring multiplication is done along the path, and the addition is between paths.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] This general framework is known as the algebraic path problem.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] Most of the classic shortest-path algorithms (and new ones) can be formulated as solving linear systems over such algebraic structures.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] More recently, an even more general framework for solving these (and much less obviously related problems) has been developed under the banner of valuation algebras.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] In real-life, a transportation network is usually stochastic and time-dependent.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The travel duration on a road segment depends on many factors such as the amount of traffic (origin-destination matrix), road work, weather, accidents and vehicle breakdowns.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] A more realistic model of such a road network is a stochastic time-dependent (STD) network.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] There is no accepted definition of optimal path under uncertainty (that is, in stochastic road networks).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] It is a controversial subject, despite considerable progress during the past decade.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] One common definition is a path with the minimum expected travel time.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The main advantage of this approach is that it can make use of efficient shortest path algorithms for deterministic networks.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] However, the resulting optimal path may not be reliable, because this approach fails to address travel time variability.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] To tackle this issue, some researchers use travel duration distribution instead of its expected value.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] So, they find the probability distribution of total travel duration using different optimization methods such as dynamic programming and Dijkstra's algorithm .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] These methods use stochastic optimization, specifically stochastic dynamic programming to find the shortest path in networks with probabilistic arc length.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The terms *travel time reliability* and *travel time variability* are used as opposites in the transportation research literature: the higher the variability, the lower the reliability of predictions.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] To account for variability, researchers have suggested two alternative definitions for an optimal path under uncertainty.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] The *most reliable path* is one that maximizes the probability of arriving on time given a travel time budget.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/shortest-path-problem] An *α-reliable path* is one that minimizes the travel time budget required to arrive on time with a given probability.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] In mathematics, a **dense graph** is a graph in which the number of edges is close to the maximal number of edges (where every pair of vertices is connected by one edge).
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] The opposite, a graph with only a few edges, is a **sparse graph**.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] The distinction of what constitutes a dense or sparse graph is ill-defined, and is often represented by 'roughly equal to' statements.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] Due to this, the way that density is defined often depends on the context of the problem.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] Consider a simple graph $(V,E)$ where V is the set of vertices and E is the set of edges.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] We write $|V|$ to denote the number of vertices, and $|E|$ to denote the number of edges.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] The **graph density** of the simple graph $(V,E)$ is defined to be the ratio of the number of edges |*E*| with respect to the maximum possible edges.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] The maximum number of edges for an undirected graph is ${\binom {|V|}{2}}={\frac {|V|(|V|-1)}{2}}$ , so the maximal density is 1 (for complete graphs) and the minimal density is 0.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] For families of graphs of increasing size, one often calls them sparse if $D\rightarrow 0$ as $|V|\rightarrow \infty$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] Sometimes, in computer science, a more restrictive definition of sparse is used like $|E|=O(|V|\log |V|)$ or even $|E|=O(|V|)$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] In this same context, a dense graph may be defined as any graph where |*E*| is "close" to $|V|^{2}$ .
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] Lee & Streinu (2008) and Streinu & Theran (2009) define a graph as being (*k*, *l*)-sparse if every nonempty subgraph with n vertices has at most *kn* − *l* edges, and (*k*, *l*)-tight if it is (*k*, *l*)-sparse and has exactly *kn* − *l* edges.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] Thus trees are exactly the (1,1)-tight graphs, forests are exactly the (1,1)-sparse graphs, and graphs with arboricity k are exactly the (*k*,*k*)-sparse graphs.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] Pseudoforests are exactly the (1,0)-sparse graphs, and the Laman graphs arising in rigidity theory are exactly the (2,3)-tight graphs.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] Other graph families not characterized by their sparsity can also be described in this way.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] For instance the facts that any planar graph with n vertices has at most 3*n* – 6 edges (except for graphs with fewer than 3 vertices), and that any subgraph of a planar graph is planar, together imply that the planar graphs are (3,6)-sparse.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] However, not every (3,6)-sparse graph is planar.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] Similarly, outerplanar graphs are (2,3)-sparse and planar bipartite graphs are (2,4)-sparse.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] Streinu and Theran show that testing (*k*,*l*)-sparsity may be performed in polynomial time when k and l are integers and 0 ≤ *l* < 2*k*.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] For a graph family, the existence of k and l such that the graphs in the family are all (*k*,*l*)-sparse is equivalent to the graphs in the family having bounded degeneracy or having bounded arboricity.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] More precisely, it follows from a result of Nash-Williams (1964) that the graphs of arboricity at most a are exactly the (*a*,*a*)-sparse graphs.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] Similarly, the graphs of degeneracy at most d are $\left(d,{\binom {d+1}{2}}\right)$ -sparse graphs.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] Nešetřil & Ossona de Mendez (2010) considered that the sparsity/density dichotomy makes it necessary to consider infinite graph classes instead of single graph instances.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] They defined *somewhere dense* graph classes as those classes of graphs for which there exists a threshold *t* such that every complete graph appears as a *t*-subdivision in a subgraph of a graph in the class.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] To the contrary, if such a threshold does not exist, the class is *nowhere dense*.
[src:johnson-all-pairs/sparse-graph] The classes of graphs with bounded degeneracy and of nowhere dense graphs are both included in the biclique-free graphs, graph families that exclude some complete bipartite graph as a subgraph.
